| Nanoscale  Analysis Labs                                           |
|   from the just-add-a-drop-of-water dept.                          |
|   posted by samzenpus on Monday May 14, @08:49 (Biotech)           |
|   http://science.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/14/1151253      |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]FiReaNGeL writes "Imagine being able to rapidly identify tiny
biological molecules such as DNA and toxins using less than a drop of
salt water in a system that can fit on a microchip. It's closer than you
might believe: in a paper appearing next week in PNAS, a team of
researchers proves for the first time that [1]a single nanometer-scale
pore in a thin membrane can be used to accurately detect and sort
different-sized polymer chains (a model for biomolecules) that pass
through or block the channel. This could lead to rapid detection systems
for pathogens and toxic chemicals."

Discuss this story at:
    http://science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/14/1151253

